<|channel>thought
<channel|>**Biographies of 張釋之 and 馮唐**

張廷尉 釋之 was a man of 堵陽, courtesy name 季. He had an elder brother, 仲, with whom he lived. He served as a cavalry officer in 訾 under 孝文帝; for ten years he could not get a transfer and remained unknown. 釋之 said, "Long officialdom diminishes 仲's estate; it is not successful." He wished to resign and return home. The 中郎將 袁盎 knew of his virtue and regretted his departure, so he requested to move 釋之 to the position of 謁者. After 釋之 finished his audience at court, he stepped forward to speak on matters of convenience. 文帝 said, "Keep it humble; do not use overly lofty discourse, but suggest things that can be implemented now." Thereupon 釋之 spoke at length about the matters between 秦 and 漢, and why 秦 fell and 漢 rose. 文帝 praised him and appointed 釋之 as 謁者仆射.

While accompanying the Emperor, they ascended 虎圈. The Emperor questioned the 上林尉 regarding the registers of various birds and beasts; after more than ten questions, the 尉 looked around and was completely unable to answer. A 嗇夫 of 虎圈, standing by, answered the Emperor's questions about the registers of birds and beasts with great detail, wishing to show his ability to respond fluently and endlessly. 文帝 said, "Should an official not be like this? The 尉 is useless!" He then ordered 釋之 to appoint the 嗇夫 as the 上林令. After some time, 釋之 stepped forward and said, "What does Your Majesty think of 絳侯 周勃?" The Emperor said, "He is a 長者 (elder/man of virtue)." He again asked, "What of 東陽侯 張相?" The Emperor again replied, "A 長者." 釋之 said, "The 絳侯 and 東陽侯 are called 長者, yet these two can hardly speak a word on affairs; how can they be compared to this 嗇夫, who is so glib and quick-tongued! Moreover, 秦 relied on the 'brush and knife' officials; the officials competed to be hasty, harsh, and inquisitive to outdo one another, yet their failures were merely formal; they lacked the reality of compassion. For this reason, their faults were not heard, and they declined until the second emperor, when the world collapsed like earth. Now Your Majesty, because the 嗇夫 is eloquent, promotes him rapidly; I fear the world will follow like wind-blown grass, competing to be eloquent while lacking substance. Furthermore, the transformation of the lower by the upper is as fast as a shadow or an echo; the selection of officials must be scrutinized." 文帝 said, "Well said." He then stopped the appointment of the 嗇夫.

As the Emperor boarded the carriage, he called 釋之 to ride with him. Moving slowly, he asked 釋之 about the failures of 秦. 釋之 spoke the truth in detail. Upon arriving at the palace, the Emperor appointed 釋之 as 公車令.

After a while, the 太子 and the 梁王 entered the court in the same carriage. They did not descend at the 司馬門; therefore, 釋之 stopped the 太子 and 梁王, saying they could not enter the palace gate. He then impeached them for lack of respect in not descending at the public gate and submitted a memorial. 薄太后 heard of this, and 文帝 removed his cap in apology, saying, "I have not taught my sons with caution." 薄太后 then sent an envoy carrying an imperial edict to pardon the 太子 and 梁王, after which they were allowed to enter. Because of this, 文帝 found 釋之 extraordinary and appointed him as 中大夫.

Later, he became 中郎將. While accompanying the Emperor to 霸陵, they stayed at the north side facing the toilets. At that time, 慎夫人 accompanied them. The Emperor pointed to the road to 新豐 and said, "This is the road to 邯鄲." He had 慎夫人 play the zither, and the Emperor leaned against the zither and sang with a miserable and grieving heart. He looked at the ministers and said, "Alas! Using the stone of 北山 as a coffin, using 紵 cotton for lining, and sealing the gaps with lacquer, how can it be disturbed!" Everyone around said, "Well said." 釋之 stepped forward and said, "If there is something desirable within, even if 南山 is sealed, there will be a gap; if there is nothing desirable within, even without a stone coffin, why grieve!" 文帝 praised him. Afterward, he appointed 釋之 as 廷尉.

Later, the Emperor went out across 中渭橋. A man came out from under the bridge, and the imperial horses were startled. The cavalry were ordered to capture him and deliver him to the 廷尉. 釋之 interrogated him. The man said, "I am a resident of the county; hearing the imperial procession, I hid under the bridge. After a long time, thinking the procession had passed, I came out, saw the imperial carriage and cavalry, and simply ran." The 廷尉's standard was that for one person violating the imperial procession, the penalty was a fine. 文帝 said angrily, "This man personally startled my horses. My horses are fortunately gentle; had they been other horses, would they not have injured me? And the 廷尉 merely imposes a fine!" 釋之 said, "The law is a public matter shared by the Son of Heaven and the world. Now the law is thus, and if it is made heavier, the law will not be trusted by the people. Moreover, at that moment, Your Majesty could have ordered his immediate execution. Now that he has been handed to the 廷尉—the 廷尉 being the balance of the world—if it tilts, the application of law in the world will all become light or heavy; where would the people place their hands and feet? I beg Your Majesty to consider this." After a long time, the Emperor said, "The 廷尉 is correct."

Later, someone stole a jade ring from before the seat of the 高廟. He was captured, and 文帝, in anger, handed the case to the 廷尉. 釋之 examined the statutes; stealing from the ancestral temple's imperial items was to be reported to the Emperor, and the penalty for such a report was execution in the marketplace. The Emperor was furious and said, "That a person is so lawless as to steal from the temple of the late Emperor! I handed him to the 廷尉 wishing to exterminate his clan, yet you report it according to the law; this is not the intent with which I share the ancestral temple." 釋之 removed his cap, bowed his head, and apologized, saying, "The law is sufficient as it is. Moreover, while crimes are equal, they differ by whether they are rebellious or obedient. Now, if one steals a temple object and is exterminated, that is one in ten thousand; if a foolish commoner took a handful of earth from 長陵, how would Your Majesty apply the law?" After a long time, 文帝 spoke with the 太后 and permitted the 廷尉's judgment. At this time, the 中尉 條侯 周亞夫 and the 梁相 山都侯 王恬 met with 釋之 to discuss fairness, and they became close friends. From this, 張廷尉 was praised throughout the world.

After 文帝 passed away and 景帝 ascended, 釋之 was afraid and claimed illness. He wished to resign, fearing a great purge; yet he wished to apologize but did not know how. Following the plan of 王生, he finally went to apologize, and 景帝 let the matter pass.

王生 was a recluse who was skilled in the discourse of 黃老. He was once summoned to the court, where the 三公 and 九卿 all gathered. 王生 was old and said, "My shoe-strap is loose," and looked at 張廷尉, saying, "Tie my shoe-strap for me!" 釋之 knelt and tied it. Afterward, someone asked 王生, "Why did you humiliate 張廷尉 in court by making him kneel to tie your shoe-strap?" 王生 said, "I am old and lowly; I estimate I will be of no benefit to 張廷尉. 張廷尉 is currently a famous minister of the world; therefore, I slightly humiliated the 廷尉 by making him kneel to tie my shoe-strap, wishing to increase his weight (importance)." The ministers heard this, admired 王生, and respected 張廷尉.

張廷尉 served 景帝 for over a year and then became the 相 of 淮南王, still being regarded for his previous merits. After a long time, 釋之 died. His son was called 張摯, courtesy name 長公, who rose to the rank of 大夫 and then resigned. Because he could not fit in with the people of his time, he remained out of official service for the rest of his life.

As for 馮唐, his grandfather was a man of 趙. His father moved to 代. When 漢 rose, he moved to 安陵. 唐 was known for his filial piety and became a 中郎署長, serving 文帝. As 文帝's carriage passed, he asked 唐, "Old man, why are you a 郎? Where is your home?" 唐 answered truthfully. 文帝 said, "When I lived in 代, the 尚食監 高袪 often spoke to me of the virtue of the 趙 general 李齊, who fought at 鉅鹿. Now, every time I eat, my mind is always at 鉅鹿. Do you know of this?" 唐 replied, "He was not as good a general as 廉頗 or 李牧." The Emperor asked, "Why?" 唐 said, "My grandfather, when in 趙, was a general and was close to 李牧. My father was the 相 of 代 and was close to the 趙 general 李齊; he knew his character." After the Emperor heard of the characters of 廉頗 and 李牧 and found it a good explanation, he slapped his thigh and said, "Alas! Had I only had 廉頗 and 李牧 as my generals, how could I worry about the 匈奴!" 唐 said, "My Lord! Even if Your Majesty had 廉頗 and 李牧, you would not be able to use them." The Emperor was angry, rose, and entered the inner palace. After a long time, he summoned 唐 and scolded him, "Why do you humiliate me publicly and leave no room for privacy?" 唐 apologized, saying, "This lowly person did not know the taboos."

At that time, the 匈奴 had recently entered the court to pay tribute but killed the 北地都尉 卬. The Emperor was concerned about the 胡 bandits, so he again asked 唐, "Why do you know that I would not be able to use 廉頗 and 李牧?" 唐 replied, "I have heard that when the kings of antiquity sent generals, they knelt and pushed the carriage, saying: 'That which is inside the 閫 (gate) is decided by me; that which is outside the 閫 is decided by the general.' Military merits and rewards were all decided outside and reported upon return. This is not empty talk. My grandfather said that when 李牧 was a 趙 general stationed at the border, the taxes from the military markets were all used to feast the soldiers; rewards were decided outside and not interfered with from the center. He was entrusted with authority and held responsible for success; thus 李牧 was able to exhaust his intelligence. He deployed 1,300 chariots, 13,000 cavalry, and 100,000 soldiers of a hundred gold. Thus he drove the 單于 north, defeated the 東胡, destroyed 澹林, suppressed the strong 秦 to the west, and supported 韓 and 魏 to the south. At that time, 趙 almost became the hegemon. Later, the 趙 king 遷 was established, whose mother was a singer. After 遷 was established, he used the slander of 郭開 and finally executed 李牧, letting 顏聚 replace him. Thus the army was defeated, the soldiers fled north, and they were captured and destroyed by 秦. Now I humbly hear that 魏尚, as the 雲中守, used all the military market taxes to feast the soldiers, and spent his own money to slaughter an ox every five days to feast guests, officers, and attendants; thus the 匈奴 avoided him and did not approach the 雲中 pass. Whenever the barbarians entered, 尚 led chariots and cavalry to strike them, killing many. The soldiers are all sons of families who rose from the fields to join the army; how would they know the intricacies of registers and tallies? They fight hard all day, beheading and capturing prisoners, and report their merits to the 莫府, yet not a word is responded to; the clerks bind them with the law. Their rewards are not implemented, while the clerks insist on the law. I am foolish, but I believe Your Majesty's law is too clear, the rewards too light, and the punishments too heavy. Moreover, the 雲中守 魏尚 was penalized because his reported merits and captured heads differed by six grades; Your Majesty ordered the clerks to strip his rank and make him a penal laborer. From this it can be said that even if Your Majesty had 廉頗 and 李牧, you would not be able to use them. I am truly foolish and have touched a taboo; it is a death offense, a death offense!" 文帝 was pleased. That day, he ordered 馮唐 to carry the tally to pardon 魏尚, restore him as 雲中守, and appointed 唐 as 車騎都尉, in charge of the 中尉 and the chariots and soldiers of the commanderies and states.

In the seventh year, 景帝 ascended and made 唐 the 楚相, then dismissed him. When 武帝 ascended, he sought the virtuous and upright, and 馮唐 was recommended. 唐 was then over ninety years old and could no longer serve as an official, so he put his son 馮遂 as a 郎. 遂, courtesy name 王孫, was also an extraordinary man and was a friend of mine.

The Grand Historian says: 張季's words on the 長者, and his adherence to the law without flattering intentions; 馮公's discourse on leading generals—how flavorful! How flavorful! The saying goes, "If you do not know a person, look at his friends." The praise these two received can be recorded in the halls of government. The books say, "Not biased and not partisan, the King's Way is vast; not partisan and not biased, the King's Way is smooth." 張季 and 馮公 came close to this. [end of text]


